[![](https://globalvoices.org/wp-
content/uploads/2017/03/MG_9890-800x450.jpg)](https://globalvoices.org/wp-
content/uploads/2017/03/MG_9890.jpg)

Supporters cheer for the Afghan team during a T20 match in India. Image by
Ieshan Wani.

The game of cricket is a great cause of hope and joy in war-torn Afghanistan.
The team is a rising star in the sport, which a generation of players learned
in the refugee camps of Pakistan.

Even when the team is playing abroad, cricket seems to have the power to
[unite a country](https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28685177-the-corridor-
of-uncertainty) defined by violence and factionalism. Afghanistan's team has
been doing just that throughout the month of March, as it [goes head to head
with the Ireland cricket
team](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_cricket_team_against_Afghanistan_in_India_in_2016%E2%80%9317)
in a Twenty20 International series in India.

Afghanistan is technically the host team in this match-up, given that they
[signed a contract](http://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/greater-noida-
stadium-to-be-home-ground-for-afghanistan-cricket-team/story-
BdLrzzR2j1vWeN311dLO5L.html) with the Board of Control for Cricket in India to
designate Greater Noida's Shaheed Vijay Singh Pathak stadium as their home
ground. On Wednesday, March 8, Afghanistan [defeated
Ireland](http://afghanistantimes.af/afghanistan-beat-ireland-by-6-wickets/) by
six wickets, but the taste of victory was soon tainted as ISIS claimed to have
[carried out](http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/03/investigation-isil-claim-
kabul-hospital-attack-170309055515857.html) a [deadly attack on Afghanistan's
largest military hospital in Kabul](http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-
news/death-toll-in-islamic-state-attack-on-kabul-military-hospital-rises-
to-49/story-xfEjvB7E8YTtKxh3Y9c6lN.html), which killed 49 people.

“Afghanistan cricket team is our one happiness in all the pain we have had. It
has brought entire nation together as everyone from different ethnicities
watch and cheer for them but the entire nation went into mourning on Wednesday
despite the win,” Asadullah, a student in Delhi waving the Afghan flag, told
_Global Voices_.

Two days later, both teams assembled to pay homage to people killed in the
attack ahead of the [2nd T20 International
game](http://www.espncricinfo.com/afghanistan-v-
ireland-2016-17/content/story/1086310.html) on March 10, 2017. The Afghanistan
team wore black bands on their right arms in solidarity with the victims, as
flocks of dark clouds brooded over the ground, occasionally yielding to
sunnier spells, only to return again later.

