> 2017](https://twitter.com/FFazly/status/840118136615587843)

Afghanistan's powerful batsman Mohammad Shahzad was the first back in the
dressing room after being caught as he tried to clear mid-off.

The clouds thickened as wickets continued to fall, despite a flurry of sixes
courtesy of Najeeb Tarakai who helped Afghanistan to post a [strong total of
184 on the board](http://www.espncricinfo.com/afghanistan-v-
ireland-2016-17/content/story/1086310.html).

Some spectators used the occasion to draw attention to the country's plight. A
young Afghan boy in attendance held a placard that read “International
politics stop killing us”. Some of his friends applied red paint over their
face, representing blood.

[![](https://globalvoices.org/wp-
content/uploads/2017/03/MG_9837-800x450.jpg)](https://globalvoices.org/wp-
content/uploads/2017/03/MG_9837.jpg)

Placard held by spectators. Image by Ieshan Wani.

The matches are being hosted in India because of security concerns in
Afghanistan, but ironically, cricket is a rare patch of common ground between
the recalcitrant Taliban and the government. In 2012, the [Taliban lent
support](http://www.espncricinfo.com/other/content/story/552874.html) to the
national team when it was facing of with Pakistan in the United Arab Emirates,
while in 2015 the [Taliban and government forces reportedly both fired their
guns — not on each other, but in joy –](http://sabotagetimes.com/life/how-the-
taliban-helped-cricket-to-flourish-in-afghanistan) after the team qualified
for the World Cup.

