[![](https://globalvoices.org/wp-
content/uploads/2017/03/MG_9859-800x450.jpg)](https://globalvoices.org/wp-
content/uploads/2017/03/MG_9859.jpg)

The sky was gloomy, but the game went on. Image by Ieshan Wani

The floodlights were switched on as the Irish team came to the crease to try
and match Afghanistan's total. The nature of T20, in which each team has just
20 overs or 120 balls to rack up a score, means the batting team has to start
quickly. Ireland rose to the challenge, hitting balls out the ground from the
off as rain began to fall.

[![](https://globalvoices.org/wp-
content/uploads/2017/03/MG_9908-800x450.jpg)](https://globalvoices.org/wp-
content/uploads/2017/03/MG_9908.jpg)

The Afghan team cheers the fall of an Irish wicket. Image by Ieshan Wani.

Eventually the rain forced a stop in play as players rushed to the dugout and
covers were drawn over the pitch.

> Oh, rain please go away, coz we are going to
> lose.[#AfgvsIre](https://twitter.com/hashtag/AfgvsIre?src=hash)
> [@ACBofficials](https://twitter.com/ACBofficials)
